Inventory Login Portal · v0.1

§ 01 · Introduction
1.1 · Purpose

This document provides a detailed description of the requirements for the Inventory Login Portal. It is intended for developers, testers, project managers, and stakeholders to understand system functionality, constraints, and expected behavior. It will also serve as a reference for system validation and future enhancements.

1.2 · Scope of the Product

Product name: Inventory Login Portal

What the product will do:
The Inventory Login Portal is a web-based interface that allows users to securely log in to an office inventory management system. It collects user credentials including email, password, and division, validates the inputs, and prepares authentication for accessing inventory-related features such as requesting items and managing stock.

What the product will NOT do:
The system will not handle full inventory management operations such as adding, updating, or deleting inventory items. It will not provide advanced authentication like biometric login or multi-factor authentication in the current version. It also does not include backend authentication or database integration in this phase.

Benefits / goals:
The system aims to simplify user access to the inventory platform, ensure basic validation of login credentials, and provide a clean, responsive user interface for better user experience.

Applicability:
This system is intended for office employees, administrators, and staff who need access to the inventory management system through a web browser.

1.3 · Definitions, Acronyms, Abbreviations
| Term | Meaning                             |
| ---- | ----------------------------------- |
| SRS  | Software Requirements Specification |
| UI   | User Interface                      |
| HTML | HyperText Markup Language           |
| CSS  | Cascading Style Sheets              |
| Auth | Authentication                      |


1.4 · References

ISO/IEC/IEEE 29148:2018 — Requirements Engineering
HTML5 Specification
CSS3 Specification

1.5 · Overview of this Document

This document describes the system from a high-level overview to detailed functional and non-functional requirements. Section 2 explains the overall system, Section 3 defines detailed requirements, Section 4 explains verification, and Section 5 includes supporting materials.

§ 02 · Overall Description

2.1 · Product Perspective

The Inventory Login Portal is a standalone front-end module that will later integrate with a backend authentication system.

System interfaces: Backend authentication server (future)
User interfaces: Web browser interface
Hardware interfaces: Desktop and laptop
Software interfaces: Web browsers (Chrome, Edge, Firefox)
Communication interfaces: HTTP/HTTPS
Memory constraints: Minimal (lightweight frontend)
Operations: Normal mode only
Site adaptation: Responsive design for different screen sizes

2.2 · Product Functions

The system provides the following major functions:

Display login interface
Accept user credentials (email, password, division)
Validate required fields
Submit login form
Provide basic UI feedback

2.3 · User Characteristics

| User Class | Description              | Expertise | Frequency    |
| ---------- | ------------------------ | --------- | ------------ |
| Admin      | Manages inventory system | Expert    | Daily        |
| Employee   | Requests inventory items | Basic     | Weekly       |
| IT Support | Maintains system         | Expert    | Occasionally |



2.4 · Constraints
Must be developed using HTML and CSS
Must run on modern web browsers
No backend integration in current version
Must be responsive
Must follow basic UI/UX standards

2.5 · Assumptions and Dependencies
Users have internet access
Browsers support modern HTML5 and CSS3
Backend authentication will be implemented later

2.6 · Apportioning of Requirements

Future versions may include:

Microsoft login integration
Backend authentication
Role-based access

§ 03 · Specific Requirements
3.1 · External Interface Requirements
3.1.1 · User Interfaces
Clean login form layout
Input fields for email, password, division
Login button
Responsive design
Error messages for invalid input

3.1.2 · Hardware Interfaces
Compatible with desktop and laptop

3.1.3 · Software Interfaces
Web browsers (Chrome, Edge, Firefox)

3.1.4 · Communications Interfaces
HTTP/HTTPS protocol

3.2 · Functional Requirements
FR-01 · User Login Input
Description: System allows users to input login credentials
Inputs: Email, Password, Division
Processing: Validate non-empty fields
Outputs: Form submission
Preconditions: Page loaded
Postconditions: Data submitted
Error handling: Show validation message
Priority: Must

FR-02 · Form Validation
Description: Ensure all fields are filled
Inputs: User input fields
Processing: Check empty values
Outputs: Error message if invalid
Priority: Must

FR-03 · Responsive Design
Description: UI adapts to screen sizes
Priority: Should

3.3 · Non-Functional Requirements
3.3.1 · Performance Requirements
Page load time < 2 seconds

3.3.2 · Safety Requirements
No critical safety risks

3.3.3 · Security Requirements
Password field must be hidden
Data transmitted via HTTPS (future)

3.3.4 · Software Quality Attributes
| Attribute       | Requirement                 |
| --------------- | --------------------------- |
| Reliability     | Minimal UI errors           |
| Availability    | 99% uptime                  |
| Maintainability | Clean code structure        |
| Portability     | Works on all browsers       |
| Usability       | Easy to use                 |
| Accessibility   | Basic accessibility support |



3.3.5 · Business Rules
All fields are mandatory before login

3.5 · Other Requirements
3.5.1 · Database Requirements
Not applicable in current version

3.5.2 · Internationalisation
English language support

3.5.3 · Legal, Regulatory, Compliance
Must follow basic web standards

